(<b>Gómez</b>): from a medieval personal name, probably of Visigothic origin, from <i>guma</i> ‘man’. Compare   De Gomez  .","Jewish (Sephardic): adoption of the name in 1 above at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some Jewish descendants retained the surname that their families had adopted as Roman Catholics."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Macieira","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Galician and Portuguese: topographic name from <i>maceira</i> (derivative of <i>mazá</i> or <i>maçá</i> ‘apple’, with the locative suffix <i>–eira</i>), denoting a place where there was a single apple tree."],"variants":[{"name":"Macera","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Pasco, Alfonso, Angelo, Antonio, Giuseppe, Pasquale, Armando, Basilio, Carmine, Cosmo, Dario, Modesto, Nunzio, Pietro, Ricci, Rosaria.","Italian (southern): topographic name from <i>macera</i> ‘dry-stone wall, pile of stones (collected from cultivated land), stone ruins’.","Spanish: in some cases, possibly also a habitational name from La Macera in Cáceres province."]}]},{"name":"Lorenço","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’.  See  <b>Laurence</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Laurence","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lorenço Gomes de Macieira was born in 1135, in Portugal, his father, Gomes Pires de Maceira, was 40 and his mother, Marinha Osores Pais  de BARVAENS, was 0. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Marina Paez de Barvaens. He was buried in Portugal."},"et":{"1135–":"1135–Surnud","1135–Male":"1135–Surnud","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1167–Female":"1167–Surnud","1181–Female":"1181–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1095–Male":"1095–Surnud","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1135":"1135","1167":"1167","1095":"1095","1172":"1172","1182":"1182","1181":"1181","about 1153":"umbes 1181","Portugal":"Portugal","Portugal, Portugal":"Portugal, Portalegre, Portugal"},"fi":{"1135–":"1135–Kuollut","1135–Male":"1135–Kuollut","1172–Female":"1172–Kuollut","1167–Female":"1167–Kuollut","1181–Female":"1181–Kuollut","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1095–Male":"1095–Kuollut","1135–Female":"1135–Kuollut","about 1182":"noin 1182","1135":"1135","1167":"1167","1095":"1095","1172":"1172","1